## Lab Walkthrough

### Syntax: Get-Command -Commandtype "Function"

PS C:\Users\captain> Get-Command -CommandType "Function"

CommandType     Name                                               Version    Source                                                                                                                                     
-----------     ----                                               -------    ------
Function        A:
Function        Add-BCDataCacheExtension                           1.0.0.0    BranchCache
Function        Add-DnsClientDohServerAddress                      1.0.0.0    DnsClient
Function        Add-DnsClientNrptRule                              1.0.0.0    DnsClient
[...]

- lists all commands with the Command type "Function"
- each row is an available function
- Version(the version of the module the command comes from)
- Source(the module that provided the function)

### Syntax: Find-Module -Name "Powershell"

PS C:\Users\captain> Find-Module -Name "PowerShell*"   

Version    Name                                Repository           Description 
-------    ----                                ----------           ----------- 
0.4.7      powershell-yaml                     PSGallery            Powershell module for serializing and deserializing YAML

2.2.5      PowerShellGet                       PSGallery            PowerShell module with commands for discovering, installing, updating and publishing the PowerShell artifacts like Modules, DSC Resources, Role Capabilities and Scripts.                                                   
1.0.80.0   PowerShell.Module.InvokeWinGet      PSGallery            Module to Invoke WinGet and parse the output in PSOjects

0.17.0     PowerShellForGitHub                 PSGallery            PowerShell wrapper for GitHub API  

- Find-Module function searched a repository called PSGallery for 'modules whose name starts with Powershell'
- found (4) matching modules
- Version(the available version of the module)
- Name(module name)
- Repository(where Powershell found the module)
- Description(short description of what the module does)

## Security Relevance
- cybersecurity uses Powershell for administration, triage and automation
- attackers may use Powershell for execution of malware and discovery
- Powershell abuse is a known technique in MITRE ATT&CK
- Powershell should be configured and monitored as part of any security posture

